{"add":{"doc":{"id":"202d1da8364cdf2fae11fc84e4e9d440d6efe50b608bec77dc5876dac9d028e0","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Anders_Zorn_-_Hins_Anders_%281904%29.jpg/220px-Anders_Zorn_-_Hins_Anders_%281904%29.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Like many other instruments used in classical music, the violin descends from remote ancestors that were used for folk music. Following a stage of intensive development in the late Renaissance, largely in Italy, the violin had improved (in volume, tone, and agility), to the point that it not only became a very important instrument in art music, but proved highly appealing to folk musicians as well, ultimately spreading very widely, sometimes displacing earlier bowed instruments. Ethnomusicologists have observed its widespread use in Europe, Asia, and the Americas."]}}}